          <!-- PROLOGUE – FULLY POLISHED & EXPANDED -->
          <article id="panel-prologue" class="chapter-panel active">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Prologue – World Government, 2050</em></p>

            <p>
              By the middle of the century, the arguments were finally over. After decades of
              marches, riots and back-room negotiations, the flags came down one by one, and the
              old United Nations rebranded itself as something new – and far more powerful. The
              world did not wake up to fanfare or fireworks, just a simple push notification:
              <em>“UN Resolution 0: The One World Government framework is now in force.”</em>
            </p>

            <p>
              For most people, nothing changed at nine o’clock that morning. They still made
              coffee, still argued with partners, still shouted at the news. But beneath the surface,
              the machinery shifted. Laws that had taken years to wrangle were stamped through in
              days. The first priority was simple and brutally efficient:
              <em>accelerate artificial intelligence everywhere</em>.
            </p>

            <p>
              AI didn’t just mean clever phones and chatty assistants anymore. It ran ports and
              freight hubs, police drones and border crossings. It scheduled surgeries, wrote legal
              briefs, priced crops, and calculated how many humans could be replaced on any given
              production line without causing riots. The new world government sold it as
              compassion: automation for the boring jobs, dignity for the workers, and a
              <em>Universal Allowance</em> wired straight into every citizen’s account.
            </p>

            <p>
              To make it work, they needed a way to follow every transaction, every journey, every
              life. So, slowly at first, then all at once, came the implants.
            </p>

            <p>
              The chip was the size of a grain of rice, pressed under the skin between thumb and
              forefinger in a bright white clinic that smelled of disinfectant and distant fear. It held
              your banking details, ID, health records, work history – your entire life compressed
              into a sliver of engineered crystal. You could still remember the old days, if you were
              over forty: cash in your pocket, cards in your wallet, the occasional dodgy cash-in-hand
              for a job that didn’t need to go on the books. Those days were gone.
            </p>

            <p>
              In 2050, you tapped your hand to pay for food, to unlock your front door, to board a
              bus. Government adverts showed smiling families waving their chipped hands at
              scanners: <em>“No more lost cards, no more forgotten PINs – just you.”</em>
            </p>

            <p>
              The retinal and fingerprint scanners came next. At first they were only in airports and
              high-security sites, then in banks, then in every government building, and finally in the
              self-service tills at the corner shop. “For your protection,” the adverts said, “to stop
              fraud and identity theft.” What they didn’t say was that with every scan, the system
              learned you a little better – your walk, your heartbeat, the angle of your shoulders
              when you were nervous.
            </p>

            <p>
              Crime figures plummeted. On paper, at least.
            </p>

            <p>
              In the old days there had been a black market in everything – cash, drugs, weapons,
              fake passports, borrowed identities. Now almost every transaction left a trail. The
              new AI compliance nets didn’t sleep. At two in the morning, in a dark data-centre
              under Geneva, a cluster of machines quietly flagged unusual spending spikes in
              Cartagena, a sudden flurry of midnight transfers in Lagos, a cluster of unregistered
              implants in an abandoned warehouse in Rotterdam. Armoured vans rolled out long
              before most people were awake enough to notice.
            </p>

            <p>
              The black market never completely disappeared, but it withered. Those who survived
              adapted, burrowing deeper, trading favours instead of credits, information instead of
              cash. But for the vast majority of people, crime became something that happened in
              old dramas and retro cop shows. For a while, the world felt almost civilised.
            </p>

            <p>
              Drugs were the biggest shock. In one sharp, controversial move, the One World
              Government deregulated narcotics and swallowed the entire industry whole. Heroin,
              cocaine, synthetics – all of it moved behind the glass of licensed pharmacies. You
              could still ruin your life if you tried hard enough, but you’d do it in a clean room with a
              registered dose, under flickering AI supervision, rather than in an alley with a shared
              needle. The cartels screamed, then bled, then reinvented themselves as “logistics
              consultants” and “security providers”. Governments took their profits in tax, and
              quietly diverted a slice to help pay for the Universal Allowance.
            </p>

            <p>
              The slogan was everywhere:
              <em>“No one left behind. A dignified life for every citizen.”</em>
            </p>

            <p>
              On paper it worked. The Universal Allowance kept people fed and housed, more or
              less. Poverty figures fell. So did protest numbers. It was hard to riot when missing a
              check-in could freeze your chip for “security verification”. There were still marches
              sometimes – old-school union banners, home-made placards, hand-painted slogans
              about privacy and freedom. The newscasters called them “heritage protests” and
              cut away to footage of gleaming driverless buses sliding along spotless streets.
            </p>

            <p>
              What most citizens saw was convenience: buses that always arrived on time, streets
              scrubbed by tireless cleaning drones, hospitals that operated with machine precision.
              Crime down. Wages guaranteed. The right adverts targeted at the right people at the
              right moment – a holiday just when you’d been thinking of the beach, a credit offer the
              day before rent was due.
            </p>

            <p>
              What they didn’t see were the people at the very top of the system.
            </p>

            <p>
              In glass towers and mountain chateaux, far from the chipped crowds queuing for
              their Universal Allowance, a handful of men and women watched the graphs twist
              upward: population, temperature, food demand, water scarcity. They saw the lines
              crossing years before anyone else did. They had access to the full data sets – not just
              the tidy, reassuring summaries on the news, but the raw numbers, the uncomfortable
              projections.
            </p>

            <p>
              They saw that even with automation, even with every field wired and every ocean
              scanned, there would soon be too many people and not enough food. They saw that
              climate repairs were behind schedule, that the oceans were still poisoned in places
              the adverts never showed, that the old nuclear scars were still leaking into the food
              chain. They saw that polite laws and quiet reforms were not going to be enough.
            </p>

            <p>
              So while the rest of the world tapped their chips and scrolled their feeds, the
              so-called Masters began to make other plans: bunkers buried a kilometre under the
              Alps and Rockies, cryogenic chambers cooled and tested, AI caretakers trained to
              keep watch long after flesh and bone would have failed. They funded think-tanks,
              weapons labs, genetic research, virus simulations – each project innocuous on its own,
              lethal when combined.
            </p>

            <p>
              On a quiet night, under a sky washed too clean by the latest pollution scrubbers, the
              world government congratulated itself on a job well done. Crime was low. Streets
              were safe. Everyone was chipped and accounted for. The numbers on the surface
              looked good.
            </p>

            <p>
              Deep underground, in a meeting room without windows, seven figures sat around a
              polished oak table and studied a different set of numbers – ones that didn’t fit into
              thirty-second news segments. Graphs of grain yields, freshwater supplies, birth rates,
              fish stocks. A different future taking shape.
            </p>

            <p>
              For ordinary people like Bill Walker, about to face his last day at the car plant, or
              James Buchanan-Smythe, butler to the men in the shadows, life still looked normal
              enough. A bit more controlled, a bit more convenient, but familiar. Buses ran. Shops
              opened. Football was still on at the weekend.
            </p>

            <p>
              None of them knew it yet, but the countdown had already started.
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- CHAPTER 1 – POLISHED TEASER (FULL TEXT CAN BE ADDED LATER) -->
          <article id="panel-ch1" class="chapter-panel">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Chapter One – Bill</em></p>

            <p>
              Bill’s alarm screamed into the grey morning, dragging him out of a heavy, dreamless
              sleep. For a moment he lay there, staring at the ceiling, trying to remember why his
              stomach felt tight. Then it came back to him: <em>last day at the car plant</em>.
            </p>

            <p>
              He reached out, thumbed the alarm off and turned his head. Kate was still sleeping
              beside him, hair a dark tangle on the pillow, face soft in the early light leaking through
              the smart-glass. He leaned over and kissed her forehead, holding the moment for
              half a beat longer than usual. Thirty-five years on the line and this was how it ended –
              with a payout, a handshake, and a computer deciding a robot could do his job better.
            </p>

            <p>
              The bathroom was small but familiar, the tiles a classic black-and-white Victorian
              pattern that his mate Ted had laid years ago. The power shower curved in a clean
              semi-circle of glass and chrome, still looking sharp against the peeling paint. Bill
              caught his reflection as the mirror de-fogged: mid-fifties, broad shoulders softened by
              years of canteen dinners and after-work pints, greying hair, eyes that had seen too
              many redundancies posted on the staff board.
            </p>

            <p>
              Under the needles of hot water he let his mind wander – the first day he’d walked into
              the plant at sixteen, nervous and proud; the countless shifts since; the colleagues
              laid off as AI crawled through the factory. He’d always survived – never took a sick
              day, always did what was asked. Now the last human section of the line was going
              fully automated, and his chip already knew it.
            </p>

            <p class="small">
              ▶ The full chapter follows Bill through his final shift, the AI-controlled buses, his
              meeting with Mick Doyle and the surprise £40,000 golden handshake, then his
              celebration dinner with Kate at the futuristic Far Eastern hotpot restaurant – all while
              the looming euro lottery jackpot is seeded in the background. (We can drop the full,
              fully-expanded chapter text into this panel when you’re ready.)
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- CHAPTER 2 – TEASER -->
          <article id="panel-ch2" class="chapter-panel">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Chapter Two – James Buchanan-Smythe</em></p>

            <p>
              James cradled his flat white as the coffee shop’s window projected a live feed of the
              Bern skyline – snow-dusted peaks, clean trams, the old city glowing in soft morning
              light. Out of the seven cities he rotated through, this was his favourite stop. Bern
              smelled of roasted beans, pine, and money that had been folded neatly and left to
              grow for generations.
            </p>

            <p>
              He looked every inch the discreet professional: perfectly pressed dark suit, silver
              cufflinks with a crest that meant something only to people with their own private jets,
              posture relaxed but never sloppy. Underneath it all lived the boy from a rough east
              London estate, the one who’d learned to dodge gangs and exam failure in the same
              afternoon.
            </p>

            <p>
              Butler to seven different residences, each with its own underground shelter and
              cryogenic vault, James was paid obscenely well for his trouble. The job came with
              perks – first-class flights, a pension that would make a CEO jealous, and most
              importantly, a keycard to a lift that descended a thousand metres below the Swiss
              granite to where the real insurance policies waited.
            </p>

            <p class="small">
              ▶ The full chapter follows James from the coffee shop to the mountain chateau,
              where he checks on the AI-run underground safety shelter: nuclear backup power,
              hydroponic farms, cryo-pods, medical bays and redundant AI caretakers – all
              meticulously maintained for the shadowy “masters” he serves. It sets up his access to
              secrets no one else gets to see.
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- CHAPTER 3 – TEASER -->
          <article id="panel-ch3" class="chapter-panel">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Chapter Three – Oliver Goldstein</em></p>

            <p>
              Oliver Goldstein’s office overlooked a slice of city that had been polished for the
              cameras – manicured rooftop gardens, clean transit lines, holographic adverts selling
              a future that was always just one upgrade away. His attention, however, was fixed on
              the one thing no advert could spin: numbers.
            </p>

            <p>
              On his screen, the draft of his latest report blinked back at him:
              <em>Will the World’s Food Run Out?</em> He’d been waiting on one final data packet
              from Population Expansion – the ten-year projection that would either soften his
              conclusions or harden them into something brutal. When the encrypted email finally
              landed in his inbox, he already knew which way it would go.
            </p>

            <p>
              Sixteen billion people by mid-century. Current food production nowhere near enough.
              Fisheries collapsing, topsoil thinning, fresh water growing scarce in all the wrong
              places. His cursor hovered over the title for only a second before he renamed the
              report:
              <em>We Need To Act Now.</em>
            </p>

            <p class="small">
              ▶ The full chapter shows Oliver drafting his blunt, uncomfortable report for the UN
              food and provisions council – including his suggestion of extreme policies like global
              one-child limits and intensive farming – and hints that certain powerful readers are
              less interested in feeding people than in using the crisis to reshape the world.
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- CHAPTER 4 – TEASER -->
          <article id="panel-ch4" class="chapter-panel">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Chapter Four – Bill &amp; Marcus</em></p>

            <p>
              The pub door was aluminium and glass, but everything inside was old-world comfort:
              a long pine bar, white and grey tiles behind the optics, dark beams criss-crossing the
              ceiling. A couple of AI bar units glided silently along their tracks, topping up glasses
              and wiping surfaces with mechanical precision while retro rock hummed in the
              background.
            </p>

            <p>
              Marcus was already in his usual spot, elbow leaning on the bar, pint in hand. His hair
              was thinner now, but he still had a guitarist’s fingers – long, wiry, stained slightly from
              nicotine and hard years. When he grinned, Bill saw the same mate he’d once shared
              tents, cheap beer and dodgy gigs with.
            </p>

            <p>
              They talked like they always did – about the past, about “Chunky” and the exploding
              tin of beans, about how the old, filthy diesel buses had somehow morphed into
              whisper-quiet AI fleets. Over more pints than they should have had, Bill dropped the
              first hint about a holiday, then about Benidorm, then – much later – about the world
              cruise he was already dreaming of, long before the numbers on his lottery ticket
              changed everything.
            </p>

            <p class="small">
              ▶ The full chapter gives a detailed, character-rich night in the pub: banter, backstory,
              and the slow unfolding of Bill and Marcus’s friendship as they agree on weekly
              meet-ups and plant the seed of the future holiday to “Blackpool with sun” – Benidorm.
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- CHAPTER 5 – TEASER -->
          <article id="panel-ch5" class="chapter-panel">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Chapter Five – James in Annecy</em></p>

            <p>
              In Annecy, the air smelled of lake water, baking bread and money on holiday. James
              walked past parasols and café tables spilling into the street, the mountains rising like
              a painted backdrop beyond the blue water. He’d done this circuit so many times he
              could walk it half-asleep, but today he was wide awake. Today was about insurance.
            </p>

            <p>
              His contact arrived on time – tall, in black, carrying a slim briefcase that didn’t match
              the casual tourist crowds. There were pleasantries, coffee orders, small talk for the
              benefit of the AI waiter’s recording, and then the real pitch: a second, illegal implant.
              One that could override almost any system, display any PIN, unlock any door with the
              help of a smart “skeleton key” that could morph to match any lock in the database.
            </p>

            <p>
              Seventy-five thousand pounds for a chip, an EMP device the size of a lighter, and a
              key that could open doors his current employers would never dream of giving him
              access to. For anyone else it would have been madness. For James, who’d spent his
              life serving people who always had a backup plan, it felt like simple symmetry.
            </p>

            <p class="small">
              ▶ The full chapter walks through the tense café meeting, the details of the illegal
              bundle James orders, and his conflicted excitement as he returns to the chateau
              imagining a life where he isn’t just a servant to the Masters – but has a way out if their
              plans ever go wrong.
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- CHAPTER 6 – TEASER -->
          <article id="panel-ch6" class="chapter-panel">
            <p class="lead-in"><em>Chapter Six – Bill’s Big Win</em></p>

            <p>
              Kate was still asleep when Bill slipped quietly out of the hotel room and headed for
              the breakfast buffet. Benidorm mornings had a particular feel – that mix of frying bacon,
              cheap perfume, and sunshine already burning through last night’s hangovers.
            </p>

            <p>
              He piled his plate high – bacon, eggs, sausage, mushrooms, beans, toast – then sat
              with a coffee and finally opened the email from the National Lottery that had been
              niggling at him since it arrived.
            </p>

            <p>
              He expected forty quid, maybe a hundred if the universe was feeling generous.
              Instead he found numbers his brain refused to process at first:
              <em>£1,567,898,431.65</em>.
            </p>

            <p>
              His hands shook so much he nearly dropped the phone. The email was clinical in its
              wording – draw number, verification details, instructions to call a special number – but
              the reality hit him in expanding waves. A lifetime on the line, and now more money
              than he could spend in ten lifetimes. He almost ran back to the room to wake Kate,
              heart hammering, words tripping over each other as he tried to tell her they were, in
              fact, billionaires.
            </p>

            <p class="small">
              ▶ The full chapter follows Bill and Kate from disbelief to Barcelona: the verification
              process, the discreet lottery officials, the magnum of Cristal, the refusal of publicity
              and the first serious conversation about what to do with a fortune big enough to
              change more than just their own lives.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <script>
    const buttons = document.querySelectorAll(".chapter-btn");
    const panels = {
      prologue: document.getElementById("panel-prologue"),
      ch1: document.getElementById("panel-ch1"),
      ch2: document.getElementById("panel-ch2"),
      ch3: document.getElementById("panel-ch3"),
      ch4: document.getElementById("panel-ch4"),
      ch5: document.getElementById("panel-ch5"),
      ch6: document.getElementById("panel-ch6")
    };
    const contentTitle = document.getElementById("contentTitle");

    buttons.forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener("click", () => {
        const target = btn.getAttribute("data-chapter");

        // update active button
        buttons.forEach(b => b.classList.remove("active"));
        btn.classList.add("active");

        // update active panel
        Object.keys(panels).forEach(key => {
          panels[key].classList.remove("active");
        });
        panels[target].classList.add("active");

        // update title text
        switch (target) {
          case "prologue":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Prologue";
            break;
          case "ch1":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Chapter 1 – Bill";
            break;
          case "ch2":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Chapter 2 – James Buchanan-Smythe";
            break;
          case "ch3":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Chapter 3 – Oliver Goldstein";
            break;
          case "ch4":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Chapter 4 – Bill & Marcus";
            break;
          case "ch5":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Chapter 5 – James in Annecy";
            break;
          case "ch6":
            contentTitle.textContent = "Chapter 6 – Bill’s Big Win";
            break;
        }
      });
    });
  </script>
